---

Background — why this matters:

Tauri passes data between Rust and TypeScript as JSON.
Rust uses snake_case field names by convention.
TypeScript/JavaScript uses camelCase by convention.

Without #[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]:

  Rust struct field:     primary_keys
  JSON produced:         {"primary_keys": [...]}
  TypeScript receives:   result.primaryKeys → undefined
                         result.primary_keys → correct

This means every multi-word field silently fails on the
TypeScript side. The app compiles and runs but data never
flows correctly. This is one of the most common Rust+Tauri
bugs and the hardest to debug because there are no errors —
just undefined values.

The fix is one annotation per struct. It must be applied
to every public struct and enum that crosses the Tauri
IPC boundary.

